This semester I am taking a writing for children class. We are focusing on writing picture books.  Over the course of the semester we get to write about a dozen picture books.  The professor has assured us they don't have to necessarily be good, but that we will learn to get ideas out onto paper.  In doing so, some of them may be "good"  -- so,  for the remainder of the semester I will be doing a story a week.  We will take the stories to class and workshop them with the other students. We will also research and learn about the publishing submission process. I think it will be a good learning experience for me.  So with that in mind.  I present to you my first attempt at a children's picture book. It is an ABC book called, "A Prickle of Porcupines"  I imagine it being a brightly colored book with each page depicting the described action. Keep in mind that this is a first draft. As always, comments and suggestions are invited.
   Sue/KyneWynn 

A Prickle of Porcupines 
(An ABC Book) 


An army of ants moving bits of bread. 

A cloud of bats flying  over the bay. 

A caravan of camels plodding through sand. 

A raft of ducks floating on the pond. 

A parade of elephant trumping at dawn.  

A charm of finches sweetly trilling a tune. 

A kindergarten of giraffes munching on leaves. 

A cackle of hyenas jumping up and down. 

A swarm of insects buzzing around. 

A scold of jays squawking in a  tree. 

A troop of kangaroos roaming the plain. 

A leap of leopards lying in the sun. 

A stream of minnows streaking by.

A watch of nightingales singing sweet songs. 

A romp of otters splashing around. 

A prickle of porcupines fanning their quills. 

A covey of quail hiding in the reeds. 

A bury of rabbits sleeping underground. 

A shiver of sharks circling in the ocean. 

An ambush of tigers stalking their prey.

A blessing of unicorns fleeing through the forrest.

A nest of vipers baring their fangs. 

A pack of wolves howling proud. 

A yoke of oxen pulling a plow. 

A herd of yak bedding down.

A zeal of zebras thundering across the savannah

Today is a missing day.  I don't know why, but today I am missing Kelly in an achey, teary eyed, heart catching, sort of way.  It's not like I don't miss him every day, I do.  But today,  I am letting myself think about how I'm missing him, and just what it is I'm missing. Today, I'm not pushing the feeling aside with busy -- ness.   I miss his smile, how one corner of his mouth lifted up a little more than the other.  I miss the lilt in his  voice when he called me, 'darlin".   I miss his arms wrapped around me in a hug. I miss watching his eyes crinkle up when something I said or did made him laugh.  I miss the way he absently ran his fingers through his hair, and how good he looked in jeans and a t-shirt,  or on stage playing his guitar and  enjoying the people enjoying the music. I miss how excited he got about springtime,  and planting things, (even though I hate gardening!) --  I liked his excitement.  I miss how our steps fit together, stride for stride when we went for a walk.   I miss how he would come home for work, and kiss me hello.  I miss his fingers tangled in my curly hair. I miss how my head fit so perfectly in the hollow of his shoulder.  I miss how he would say,  "You're the most gorgeous woman in the whole wide world."  -- His answer for any situation where he didn't want to say the wrong thing, like when I asked him if the dress I was wearing looked good.  It was a glib answer,  but I knew he meant it,  to him, I was the most gorgeous woman in the whole wide world.  I miss that, being the most important person in someones life.  I guess that, is what I am really missing today.

Okay, I only need to write three more poems for this unit. Here's one that is a little different, at least as far as form, and I need to write another sonnet as well. Just one more to go. ;)
-- Drats, when I posted this, it didn't stay in the shape-- imagine the poem centered, and it looks kind of like a butterfly. :) Sue


Transformation

Caterpiller 
Fuzzy Green 
Earthbound Coocoon Delicate Thread
Emerging Winged Flitting
Shimmering Gossamer
Butterfly




On A Sun Drenched Afternoon

On a sun drenced afternoon
I hear the distant
hum of bees
The fresh scented clover
cushions my back
as I gaze at
wind swept trees
the branches drift
to and fro
From lofty heights they wave
as I watch and dream below,
on a sun drenced day.

Okay,  since I can't sleep anyway -- I will transpose something from my writing journal that is happier than the most recent posts.  It is a description of my friends' kitchen. .. 

I sit in the kitchen. It is yellow-- not overwhelming yellow -- the walls a creamy yellow,  the cupboards and floors echoing with their golden hue.  This smooth color lends itself to the homey feel in the room. 

There are splashes of color,  a counterpoint to the softness,  a bright red toaster,  crock,  and soap dispenser.  Contrast provided in the form of a large jar of green, yellow and purple fruit on the counter. A bright red bowl of filled with apples sits on the table.  A duo of table cloths, yellow over red declare it the center of the kitchen,  and the kitchen is perhaps the center of this home. 

Warm and inviting, it bespeaks of genial conversation over familiar dishes -- a place for connection and renewal.  The family connection that means home, the yellow of welcome and warmth.

Okay, so I have to turn in 10 more poems for this poetry unit. These are some rough drafts of some poems I've started, suggestions,  comments, etc. are welcome.  There is kind of a theme -- that of loss,  guess that's where I am right now, and I can't seem to write happy poetry on demand. (sigh) -- Oh,  and if you would be so kind as to  sign your comments with at least a first name, that would be great- as that way I know who is talking to me -- unless of course you really do want to be anonymous. 

     Silence  

Silence awakens me,
reaching out to emptiness
Stumbling, sleepy still
I make my way upstairs, 
To urge him to come sleep. 

TV blaring, flickering light
I turn it off,  sudden silence
Turning I see him  
He lies there, still, unmoving, 

He's sleeping, I think, 
He must be cold -- 
He is cold,  realization dawns, 
too cold

My mind screams noooooooo 
Surreality sets in 
confronting slack face, rolled back eyes
In controlled panic 

I breathe for him
My warm lips on his cold 
unfeeling ones
Compressions rapid -- 

Flashing lights 
Ambulance, Paramedics 
Massive confusion
Loading him, 
Then silence, again 

Sterile room 
Still form 
A shell remains 
Suffocating Silence 

Alone 




    Empty 

Empty heart
Echoed 
In empty house 

Empty bed 
echos 
his loss 

Empty arms 
ache 

Longing for 
something 
to fill 
Emptiness 
   



     Pain 

No way 
No more 
No how 
Yet knowledge 
creeps in through 
crevices, cracks, fissures 

Knowledge a wedge 
pressure builds 
until 
breaking the implacable 
wall of numbness 

rushing in 
again 
flooding, blinding, 
pain 

washes over my soul  
then ebbs 
Leaving 
battered, bruised heart
in its wake 

No way, No more, No how 
again 




   Grief 

Grief 
Endless void 
Pain filled mind 
Ragged sorrow 
Trapped Inside 

Stark 
Countenance 
Reflects void 
No intrusion 
Permitted 

Ache 
Between breasts 
Constricts breathing 
Child suffering 
All alone 




   Memories 

Memories 
like rain 
fall from 
cloudy skies 

Drops 
of water 
from ebony 
lashes cascading 

Rain 
brings spring 
New life, 
dormant no more 

Tears 
ease pain 
New Hope awaits 
cloudy memories 




   Emotion 

Emotion 
hangs in 
the air
thick clouds 
envelope 
the space 
of time 
and feeling 
suffocating 
in feelings 
of . . . 
despair 


          Stars 

Bright stars twinkling in ebony sky 
Sometimes when I look up it seems I 
Could touch the twinkling light. 

Then reaching out my hand I 
find, appearances deceive, 
stars are very far away indeed. 

Just like the stars, my healing 
is, to those who look and see 
I look and act like life is fine 

But inside, and day to day,  the 
Healing struggle slow; yet one day 
I'll reach out and touch stars' glow.

Okay -- so in writing class today,  we discussed the difference between "good" poetry  and "bad" poetry --- reading several examples of each.  Our in class assignment was to write a "bad" poem, using as many of the elements as we could  that we had discussed.  Thus,  I share with you my version of a "bad" poem - -- Unfortunately,  I didn't win the class bad poem contest-- as it was too "good" lol --- anyway,  FWIW ---  :)  Sue/KyneWynn 


Sitting On a Corn Chip 

Sitting on a corn chip
I contemplated the meaning 
of life. 
As the corn chip crumbled,
Like the Berlin Wall crumbling, 
Leaving me flat, splayed legged, dumped 

I realized, like Columbus seeing the promised land 
That the world is flat no more, 
Thus giving life meaning 
No more mysteriousness like the Mona Lisa 

Meaning,  being, seeing 
Reach out and take it 
Stretch forth your hand 
like Moses to the Lamanites 

Ponder life's meaning now
Because you never know 
When you may run out of, 
Corn Chips
